BMN correspondence 

So far, we observed that the bit string model contains a number of
problems like fermion doubling and supersymmetry violation. On the
other hand, the bit string model is equivalent to BMN sector of
the super-Yang-Mills model at any finite . This equivalence
would imply that the fermionic subsector of the BMN operators is badly
defined, at finite . (Since there is no definition for the BMN
correspondence at , this would signal a self-consistency
problem in the BMN correspondence.) Hence, in this section we
proceed to the analysis of the implications of fermion doubling at
the level of the BMN operators.

The BMN correspondence relates a class of
operators in  super-Yang-Mills model, which have a
large -charge (), to states in the closed
superstring on the pp-wave background.
The string "semantics" of the BMN language is as follows. The
light-cone superstring vacuum in the BMN language is given by the
operator
 
where  is the complex scalar component,
.

The excited string states correspond to the insertion of
"impurities" under the trace BMN-ground , according to
the following rule:
 
where  and  are, respectively, bosonic
and fermionic standard oscillator raising operators. Also, in
order to get
nonzero string modes, the insertions should be accompanied by a
factor , where  is the position of
the insertion in the row of 's. Hence, e.g. a double fermionic
insertion corresponds to
 

Thus, the BMN correspondence (language ) is formulated in
terms of words  or strings of products of 's, with
insertions of impurities and operators on the space of allowed
words. The main operators acting on words are the position  and
the shift .  gives the position  (up to a cyclic
permutation) of an insertion in the chain of 's, while 
performs a permutation of the impurity in the -th position to
the -th one.

One can define the scalar product of words 
